status_message: Editorial board member Jim Mitchell wrote a series in 2005 about how Texas' workers compensation program is broken. The Texas Tribune recently wrote a series in June on the same thing, and guess what -- nothing's changed. The system is expensive for employers, and injured workers drag a burden-of-proof anvil into hearings making it very, very difficult for them to win their case, Jim says. Oh -- and Texas is still the only state where participation in the workers compensation system is voluntary. But for how much longer? http://d-news.co/A567N (Photo: AP).
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Badminton is no cookout activity for Greg Okuonghae. He represented Nigeria in badminton mixed doubles at the 2004 Olympics in Athens and considered the best badminton player on the African continent. Today Okuonghae (oh-CON-her) has 20 young pupils under his tutelage in his Basic Badminton Academy in Far North Dallas. "We're going to train for only one hour, but it will be harder than anything you have ever done," Coach Okuonghae told an aspiring badminton star recently. "Ready, boy?" http://d-news.co/zZDWT
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Stephen Smith and his business partner, James Jeffers, old Army buddies, live near each other in Oak Cliff.  A couple of years ago, Smith, Jeffers, several chefs, a person whose enterprise is roasting coffee beans, and other foodie friends were sitting around a fire pit, talking, and trying to figure out a green model for a business. Smith and Jeffers were already planting food in their front yards, and they were already selling extra, just-picked produce to restaurants and grocers. So, the urban farming Eat The Yard venture was born: http://d-news.co/A2Ww2 (Photo: Ron Baselice/DMN).

status_message: Mexico's Senate approved a plan Wednesday to radically expand its energy sector, passing the final legislative hurdle to leave behind 76 years of state monopoly. It's big news. How big? "When we add Canada, United States and Mexico, we'll be so much bigger than OPEC," says Bernard Weinstein, associate director of the Maguire Energy Institute at SMU. "We'll be an energy colossus." And Texas is expected to play an outsized role: http://d-news.co/A2Ub4 (Photo: Bloomberg).

status_message: Madi Bishop used to drive seven hours from her home in Jonesboro, Ark., to practice and play for the select Texas Glory softball club in McKinney. Her mother estimates they spent $15,000 to $20,000 a year. For Madi, it paid off -- she got a scholarship offer and has committed to Oregon, a team that was ranked No. 1 in the country. Mansfield Timberview softball coach Donya Mooney says, "I have not had a kid receive any level of scholarship in softball without playing select ball. I have had a few not play due to the cost or play at lower levels, and it definitely hurts them in regards to recruiting." With the cost of college tuition -- and debt -- soaring, the cost of select sports is a gamble many families are willing to take: http://d-news.co/zZ8w0.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Dallas County Commissioner John Wiley Price took his seat on the court this morning for the first time since his arrest last month. Editorial board member Rudy Bush wonders, if Price interfered with progress of the Inland Port, how many hundreds, or thousands, of jobs did it cost southern Dallas residents?  "He talks a great game about bringing equality and growth to southern Dallas. He gets all up in arms if you dare suggest different," Rudy writes. "But here's the thing about abusive people. status_message:
Brad and Jennifer Livingstone's schedule is a constant grind for months at a time, ferrying three sons — Bradley, 12; Jack, 10; and Parker, 8 — to baseball practices, league games and weekend tournaments. Dallas to Frisco to Addison, and back again, on a seemingly endless circuit. Over the last three decades, sports specialization for children and teens has exploded, becoming more focused, intense and expensive than ever before.

More doesn't necessarily mean better, though. With the increased intensity comes a price — often in time and money, or in some cases, the child's interest in the sport or even their physical well being. Yet, it might be the cost of competition in today's sports climate. A spot on the freshman team might depend on the level of preparation players received at a young and younger age.

So, how did it get this way? Read the first in our four-part series on youth club sports, and use our interactive timeline to watch the progression: http://d-news.co/zRnmN.

status_message: Early one morning, Mama the elephant (left) embarks on a medical routine that many seniors would find familiar, if daunting. First, she pops some pills — 144, in her case, for conditions such as joint stiffness and fluid retention, stashed inside two dozen peanut butter sandwiches. Then it's time for some blood tests, a bath, a foot exam, a massage with the elephant version of Bengay, and a weight check. Such are the travails of a geriatric elephant. At 44, Mama has surpassed the 38-year average life expectancy for a female African elephant in captivity. She is the Dallas Zoo's oldest pachyderm and presides over a herd of five aging elephants. "The Golden Girls," as they're called, are giving keepers and veterinarians valuable experience in how to care for older animals: http://d-news.co/zhY1S (Photo: Kye R. Lee/DMN). #ICYMI

status_message:
A federal appeals court ruled Monday that the placement of a Confederate flag symbol on a Texas license plate is a free speech issue and that the state has violated the rights of the Sons of Confederate Veterans by prohibiting the Stars and Bars symbol from being used on fund-raising plates (the state attorney general's office is appealing that ruling). 

Editorial board member Tod Robberson disagrees. "It is correctly regarded by millions of Americans as a symbol of slavery. The Sons of Confederate Veterans are free to tattoo their faces, paint their houses or place this symbol all over their cars. In fact, they are free to paint their entire vehicle with the Stars and Bars if they want," he writes. "But despite the fact that the Texas license plate appears on their vehicles, those plates do not belong to them. They are property of the State of Texas. The state isn't restricting the organization's free speech. It is simply saying that, on state property, you don't have final say." 

Read more and share your thoughts: http://d-news.co/zcBDS.

status_message:
From segregated churches of East Texas to destitute slums of India, United Methodist minister Rev. Charles Moore of Allen -- shown here just before officiating his stepdaughter's wedding -- fought for human rights. Then on a Monday afternoon in June, Moore, 79, drove to his hometown of Grand Saline. In a strip mall parking lot, he set himself on fire.

Moore had delivered sermons about racism and sexism. He stood vigil against the death penalty. He went on a hunger strike to protest discrimination against gays and lesbians. But in retirement, he still saw a broken world. He questioned whether he had done enough.

Moore had intended his self-immolation to be a grand but selfless gesture to bring attention to the world's injustices. But his final act drew little notice: http://d-news.co/z9pxi.

status_message: Central American children won't be the first wave of immigrants to receive shelter in Dallas. This is Al Martínez, pointing out his photo in a 1955 yearbook from a school in Cuba. Communism-fearing Cuban parents sent about 14,000 children away in what was the biggest resettlement of unaccompanied juveniles in the Western Hemisphere. Texas leads the nation in refugee resettlement, according to the U.S. State Department. Dallas has settled refugees from war-torn nations including Vietnam and Iraq, and from parts of Africa. Nearly a decade ago, it welcomed families who fled Louisiana after Hurricane Katrina. Lanin Green cowered in her closet, clung to her 2-year-old daughter and prayed that the man who had just shot her mother wouldn't come looking for them. A green basket filled with dirty laundry offered the only shield if he did.

Green hid with her daughter for 10 long minutes early Monday, waiting for help to arrive after they awoke to the sound of gunshots and the thud of a body collapsing to the floor. The ensuing silence told her that her mother, Lahomer Anderson was dead. But Green believed her mother's boyfriend was still inside the dark apartment. "I was just terrified," Green, 23, said on Tuesday.

Police have charged Brandon Donya Hughes with murder. But with no known history of violence between the couple, Green and her family are struggling to understand what led to the shooting at the Surrey Row apartment complex in Red Bird: http://d-news.co/yIEkU.

status_message: Southern Dallas slumlord-entrepreneur Douglas T. "Chase" Fonteno sold this property at 4614 Stokes St., in the low-income neighborhood of Joppa, for $49,000 on behalf of Topletz Investments last year. The home's appraised value was only $7,800. The name Topletz Investments resonates around South Dallas as the gold standard for slumlord exploitation of the poor. The Topletz family is infamous for purchasing hundreds of bottom-quality, dilapidated houses, slapping a coat of paint on the exterior, then renting them out to low-income residents willing to accept a rickety roof over their heads. status_message:
A Border Patrol agent reads the birth certificate of Alejandro, 8 -- the only thing he brought with him as he and others crossed the Rio Grande near McAllen recently. Alejandro is one of more than 52,000 minors traveling without parents who've been caught crossing the border illegally since October.

Seventy-five years ago, the St. Louis, a German trans-Atlantic liner carrying 938 Jewish refugees, was turned away from the United States and forced to return to Europe. U.S. law didn't allow them sanctuary. 

Writes author and former Dallas Morning News reporter Christine Wicker: "The St. Louis is famous now as a failure of compassion that haunts American history. Today we are preparing to send 45,000 children back to Central American countries controlled by drug cartels that routinely torture, rape and kill children who refuse to work for them. So routinely are children menaced that their families sent them away, alone, across thousands of miles on just the slimmest of hopes that they might be safe. U.S. law doesn't allow them sanctuary. 

"They walked through some of the most hostile, hot, barren, dangerous country in the world. They were sent by poor families so terrified for their safety that they paid many thousands of dollars and entrusted their children to criminals hoping they might arrive in America and be safe.

"Our hearts are not touched by these children. We want the law enforced. This is our country. Ours. And we don't have to share it. Not now. Not 75 years ago.

"Yes, these are children whom we'll send back to be raped, maimed and killed. They aren't our children. Our children are precious."

Read more and share your thoughts: http://d-news.co/yCC21 (Photo: Jennifer Whitney/New York Times). #bordercrisis #bordercrisisDMN

status_message:
Three dams — Possum Kingdom Lake, Lake Whitney and Lake Granbury (pictured) — control the upper reaches of the Brazos River, west of Fort Worth. The Brazos is in a death grip, facing what climatologists fear may become the worst drought in Texas history, even drier than the "Big Dry Up" between 1950 and 1957 that drained the Brazos and scorched its fertile 42,000-square-mile basin. 

Across the state, the drought is intensifying. But even as climatologists forecast that the Brazos will continue to diminish in coming decades, the state wants to dam up more of the river and its tributaries to create nine more reservoirs to supply water for some 5.4 million people expected to be living in the Brazos Basin in 2060: http://d-news.co/yuWF2 (Photo: Louis DeLuca/DMN)

status_message: In case you missed it: Quietly, earlier this year, Texas DPS began requiring full sets of fingerprints from everyone who obtains a new driver's license or photo ID card and from those who come in for periodic renewals. status_message: The Dallas Police Department will be the first to admit: It doesn't do a very good job of patrolling the 20-mile-long stretch of the Trinity River Corridor. The problem is that the project is rapidly expanding from north to south, from the Elm Fork Athletic Complex to the Continental Avenue Bridge to the Trinity Skyline Trail to the under-construction Texas Horse Park to the Trinity River Audubon Center ... and the list is only getting longer. At the City Council's Transportation and Trinity River Project Committee on Monday afternoon, Assistant Chief Tom Lawrence Dallas gave the council an update on how DPD hopes to keep the corridor safe sooner or later. It might be later, he warned -- three years at least before there's a plan in place to police everything from the Elm Fork woods to the Great Trinity Forest to the hike-and-bike trails now running and cycling between the levees near downtown: http://d-news.co/ymJkd (Photo: G.J. status_message: The Dallas VA's wait time for new mental health patients is among the nation's longest. Federal data released this week shows four of the nation's top 10 VA waiting lists for such patients are at Texas facilities: in Amarillo, El Paso, Harlingen and the Dallas VA. Average wait times for new patients seeking mental health care in Texas were Amarillo, 61 days, the nation's third-longest wait; El Paso, 60 days, fourth-longest; Harlingen, 55 days, eighth-longest; and Dallas, 50 days, 10th-longest: http://bit.ly/1kmJEIq.

status_message:
Some anticipated updates for Apple users -- Execs have kicked off the company's 25th annual conference for software developers in San Fransisco. A sampling of new features that were revealed today and announcements that are expected:
-- The next version of the Mac operating system will be called Yosemite.
-- An updated iCloud will function more like Dropbox or Google Drive.
-- For iPhones and iPads, IOS 8 is widely expected to include a built-in health-management tool to help people track their vital signs, diet and sleeping habits. 
-- Watchers think Apple will announce a home automation system that would enable iPhones and iPad to become a remote control for managing lighting, security and other household appliances.

... and more. Get the latest: http://d-news.co/xxJft (Photo: Bloomberg).

status_message:
George Strait ends his 30-year career as a country music icon with a concert Saturday at AT&T Stadium in Arlington. His longstanding relationship with D-FW dates back to 1981 when a still relatively unknown cowboy born in Poteet, Texas, played Fort Worth's venerable honky-tonk, Billy Bob's Texas. He sat in with the club's house band for nearly a week on the small Honky Tonk Stage. His star rose right here in North Texas, starting with headlining shows at Billy Bob's, Lancaster's Crystal Chandelier, then Starplex, Reunion Arena, and Texas Stadium, then Pizza Hut Park, Fort Worth-Tarrant County Convention Center, AAC, and many other venues, fests and shows. 

Since the beginning, North Texas has loved George Strait: http://d-news.co/xsr3S. #DMNStrait

status_message: The Texas water plan projects that agriculture will account for the largest share of increased water use over the next half-century. On Rosewood Ranch near Ennis, 2,000 acres of wetlands sustain cattle, duck hunting, and raising crawfish, thanks to conservation practices Braddock implemented. How did a cattleman turn straight farmland into diversified wetlands? For one thing, he created a system of levees: http://d-news.co/xjANI (Photo: File 2007).

status_message: The Sunset Advisory Commission, the agency that periodically examines state government for efficiency, issued four critical reports Thursday on Texas' four social services departments. Many state programs serving mentally and physically frail adults and maltreated children are in perpetual crisis because of worker turnover, failing facilities that should be shut down, and a lack of community care, the commission reported. For instance, reviewers note that 1,350 CPS caseworkers voted with their feet last year, including one-third of child abuse investigators: http://d-news.co/xcma6.

status_message: On January 4, 2012, Rickey Dale Wyatt walked out of District Judge John Creuzot's courtroom a free man for the first time in 31 years. He's pictured here on that day holding his granddaughter for the first time. He'd been convicted of rape in 1981 but always maintained his innocence. The Innocence Project ended up discovering evidence that had been withheld by prosecutors during his trial that proved what he'd been shouting for years. How does a man get back three decades that were stolen from him? He can't. But you'd better believe Wyatt is taking everyone to court who had something to with it: http://d-news.co/wGxvP (Photo: Tom Fox/DMN).

status_message:
The historic Aldredge House on Swiss Avenue was completed in 1917, a gift from a Panhandle rancher to a bride 21 years his junior. In addition to the grand living room, morning room, sunroom and dance floor, the French Renaissance residence also boasted a conservatory to keep a year-round supply of hothouse flowers in bloom. 

For the past 40 years, the house's owners, the Dallas County Medical Society Auxiliary, have kept the property well-tended -- except for the conservatory. Besides a very large magenta bougainvillea and a very old, fat and winding philodendron, the conservatory's plants have since withered away. It long was in need of attention, especially before this weekend's Swiss Avenue Home Tour.

Enter Dallas Eagle Scout Spencer Hardin, who has been involved with gardening since kindergarten: http://d-news.co/wDkVu (Photo: Louis DeLuca/DMN).
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: The mother of an Iranian man who killed a fellow youth in a street fight kissed the feet of the victim's mother April 15 in the northern city of Nowshahr. status_message: An unveiling of a new, 24-foot obelisk at the rebuilt Griggs Park in Uptown is tentatively set for June 7. It will officially recognize Rev. Allen R. status_message:
When someone asks where you're from, how do you answer? According to a Pew survey of Americans who have moved at least once, 26 percent say it's the place they were born and raised, 22 percent said it's their current residence, 18 percent said it's where they've racked up the most years. 15 percent say it's the place of family roots, and 4 percent say it's where they went to high school. 

To some people, especially in Texas, it's a loaded question. Writes Gordon Keith (who was born in Fort Worth, lived in Mississippi, then came back to Texas), "My mother is someone who still divides people along the Mason-Dixon Line. Growing up in the Deep South left her with permanent side-eye toward those from 'up north.'" http://d-news.co/vH0L3 (Photo: Evans Caglage/DMN). 

Tell us how you define where you're "from."
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
The discussion on head health in sports turns to softball. Plano East sophomore third baseman Olivia Rosen suffered a broken nose when she was struck by a line drive in a February game. She wore a mask when she was younger but stopped because the perception was "You only wore it if you were scared." Her father has already bought her a new mask for when she returns and said he will make sure she wears it.

Softball face masks are a growing trend at Dallas-area high schools. At Richardson ISD -- which has had players suffer a broken nose, severe forehead contusion and have an ear torn partially off -- it's mandatory for all third basemen to wear a mask in practice and games. 

Learn what's required, what isn't, and why line drives have increased in softball in the last few years, then share your thoughts: http://d-news.co/vEWvI.

status_message: Some Wylie residents don't remember the gruesome ax murder in this house on Dogwood Drive in 1980, but others can't forget. The over-the-top details of the killing catapulted the small Collin County town into the national spotlight. Candace "Candy" Montgomery killed Betty Gore, the wife of Montgomery's former lover. If their story had been fiction, it would have been overwritten: a 3-foot ax, 41 wounds, a salacious affair, an improbable defense, and an astonishing acquittal. Even the date of the killing seemed ripped from a bad crime novel: Friday the 13th, June 1980: http://d-news.co/vx3U5. Also, a new Investigation Discovery channel series called "Secret Lives of Stepford Wives," will feature the killing in its 30-minute show at 9 p.m. tonight: http://d-news.co/vzibu.

status_message:
Today has been dubbed "Equal Pay Day." American women working full time earn an average $11,607 a year less than men, and in Texas, black women and Hispanic women earn 59 cents and 45 cents, respectively, for each $1 paid to white men. Those gaps hurt everyone, not just women, according to a new report by the National Partnership for Women & Families. 

"As this analysis shows, when women and their families lose thousands of dollars in critical income each year, they have significantly less money to spend on food, gas, rent and other basic necessities, and the consequences for their families and our state and national economies can be devastating," says Debra L. Ness, the group's president. 

Read more, check out our touch-point map, and share your thoughts: http://d-news.co/vwSWk.

status_message:
UPDATE on the Fort Hood shooting:

-- At least 3 military personnel remain in critical condition after Ivan Lopez, an Iraq War veteran who had been treated for mental illness, killed 3 people and wounded 16 others before committing suicide. 
-- Doctors said they expect the 3 in critical condition to survive.
-- Army Secretary John McHugh says Lopez was deployed for the final months of the Iraq war but did not see combat.
-- Lopez was not wounded in action while serving overseas, but self-reported a traumatic brain injury upon his return to the U.S. 
-- Lopez appeared to have no connections to extremist groups.
-- McHugh says Lopez had been prescribed Ambien to deal with a sleeping problem and had several mental health issues. Lopez was examined by a psychiatrist last month and was found to show no violent or suicidal tendencies.
--  Lopez had one weapon, a .45 caliber Smith and Wesson handgun, that was not registered with post authorities as required. 

More: http://d-news.co/voDWD and http://d-news.co/voE27.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: What makes a church a church, in the eyes of the IRS? All Things Considered on NPR aired a story discussing just that yesterday in a story about Marcus and Joni Lamb's Bedford-based Daystar Television Network. It's a broadcasting network, but the IRS also considers it a church, affording the Lambs' $233-million business all the protections afforded every brick-and-mortar house of worship, including tax-exempt status. The Lambs also don't have to tell the government where their money comes from or where it goes. Read more about the IRS's definition of a church, then tell us what you think: http://ow.ly/3iOTUf.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Ray Hutchison has died at 81. Hutchison, a bond lawyer and husband of former Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, was instrumental in the development of Reunion Arena, American Airlines Center, Cowboys Stadium, Texas Motor Speedway -- every stadium built in North Texas in the past four decades. He led negotiations to bring the Washington Senators to Arlington, the team that became the Texas Rangers. He also was so key to the development of DART and Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport that former Dallas mayor Ron Kirk said the airport should be named for him: http://d-news.co/verw8 (Photo: File 2012).

status_message: Remind your older loved ones and friends to avoid the "Grandparents Scam," which has evolved to include email and social media. The classic version of the scam goes like this: A fraudster calls someone who's a grandparent, claims to be someone with his or her grandchild, and says the grandchild is in need of money -- fast. Some scammers are also using the internet to research their victims and the loved ones they're impersonating, making their act even more believable than before: http://d-news.co/uXOEo (Photo: Getty).

status_message: What's your "money script?" Everyone has one, but not everyone knows what it is, says DMN personal finance writer Pamela Yip. status_message:
Meet Cleo Hearn of Lancaster, known as "Mr. Black Rodeo" in cowboy circles. Lancaster dedicated a more than 2-mile equestrian trail at Bear Creek Nature Park to the black rodeo pioneer on Feb. 28, and it's no wonder: He's been a member of the Professional Rodeo Cowboy Association since 1959 and he has been producing rodeos since 1968. His first black rodeo in Texas was in 1975 at Fair Park, and eventually that rodeo evolved into what is now Cowboys of Color. 

"I was trying to find a way to develop more black cowboys, more Indian cowboys. That was the driving force. Back then, most of the time, you'd go to a rodeo, and you'd be the only black person there," he said.

Born to a family of educators in Seminole, Okla., Hearn was 12 years old when he roped his first calf for a cash pot. Now he's 74, and he's still roping: http://d-news.co/uBPmL (Photo: Rose Baca/DMN).
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: You know the book 'Lean In: Women, Work, and the Will to Lead' by Facebook COO Sheryl Sandberg? I was too tired to do any creative, outside-the-box thinking. Trapped!," she writes. "Ladies, if we want to rule the world — or even just gain an equitable share of leadership positions — we need to stop leaning in. It's killing us." status_message:
This wooden floor installed at New Orleans' Mercedes-Benz Superdome for the 2012 NCAA Final Four is similar to the one that's soon headed to AT&T Stadium in Arlington for the final leg of this year's tournament. The journey of college basketball's most prized surface begins at the 235,000-acre Menominee Indian Reservation in Wisconsin. "People watch the game and that's our timber out there," said Jim Kaquatosh, sales manager for Menominee Tribal Enterprises. "People on the reservation are real proud they could be a part of it."

Tribal Chief Oshkosh told the Menominee in the 1800s that if they "take only the mature trees, the sick trees, and the trees that have fallen … the trees will last forever." Ever since, sustainable yield foresting practices have been a part of Menominee lore. 

Read more about the origins of the floor http://d-news.co/uwsRE and more about the Final Four coming to D-FW http://d-news.co/uwwlO (Photo: New Orleans Times-Picayune).

status_message:
What does your dream retirement look like? We can't help but be a little jealous of Allyson van Os of Dallas, 62, who lives part of her life in La Paz, Mexico, or "The Peace." It's a seaside town known for sport fishing, whales, seafood and, increasingly, Americans seeking to reinvent themselves. 

With an estimated 80 million baby boomers retiring in the coming years, Mexico looms large as an alternative place to live not just on land, but on sea. Many retirees like Allyson are living seasonally or year-round on boats, lured by the simplicity of life and lower cost of living. 

They are also searching for tranquillity, a place away from the fast pace and hectic life increasingly dominated, they say, by time pressures in an age of social media: http://d-news.co/uqQAL (Photo: Alfredo Corchado/DMN).
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
In the competition for two gates at Love Field that American Airlines must give up, Southwest Airlines saw rival Virgin America's proposal for 5 destinations and raised it by 12. 

-- That's 20 flights to 12 new nonstop cities out of Dallas Love Field in late 2014 if it gets those two coveted gates. But wait; there's more:
-- Southwest says that in 2015 they'll add an unspecified number of flights to 5 more cities. 
-- Those 17 cities total are in addition to the 15 cities to which Southwest already announced it would begin nonstop service when the Wright Amendment expires in October.

Read more: http://d-news.co/urAoe (Photo: AP). That's a lot of new cities. Which ones should Southwest choose if they win the gates?

status_message: Wylie East High School student Ivan Mejia, pictured here, was killed Saturday night after a dispute with two schoolmates about a relationship with a girl, prosecutors said at a juvenile detention hearing today. Two 16-year-old boys were taken into custody and charged Sunday with killing Mejia, 17. Wylie police said that the boys killed Mejia behind their school, on Bennett Road. On Saturday night, Garland officers encountered the two 16-year-old boys while responding to a call about a car veering off Highway 78 near Firewheel Town Center mall. status_message: Pope Francis on Thursday told the story of how he stole a rosary cross from the casket of a beloved priest. He says that when he is tempted to judge others, he taps the pouch where he keeps the cross and is thankful for the grace he has been shown. This story might strike a chord with some Dallasites who celebrated Mass at the St. Jude Chapel in downtown on Ash Wednesday. The priest at 12:30 Mass shared an old story of a man who said he would not attend Mass anymore because the place was full of thieves hypocrites and liars. The priest in the story agrees, but says, there's always room for one more. In other words, we are all sinners, but we are all given grace. What do you think about the admission of Pope Francis and the story told by our local priest? (Associated Press photo of the pope celebrating Mass on Wednesday)

status_message:
Ford Frost's family company owns 1,000 acres of rice farmland in Liberty County, outside Houston, and Frost believes that liquid waste from a disposal well next door is invading his groundwater. Can you kick your neighbor off your land 8,000 feet below the surface? The Supreme Court of Texas is considering whether someone has the grounds to do just that. 

"On its face, this case is about who owns what as you descend toward the center of the earth. But more broadly, it's about whether Texas industry should get a free pass to dispose of chemical waste wherever it pleases," writes attorney Jordan Fletcher: http://d-news.co/tS9lV (Illustration: Troy Oxford/DMN).

Eddie Farnsworth and other Arizona lawmakers voted last night to let businesses refuse to serve gays on religious grounds. The 33-27 vote by the House sends the legislation to Republican Gov. Jan Brewer. Similar religious protection legislation has been introduced in Ohio, Mississippi, Idaho, South Dakota, Tennessee and Oklahoma, but Arizona's plan is the only one that has passed. 

Democrats called the proposal "state-sanctioned discrimination" and an embarrassment. Republicans stressed that the bill is about protecting religious freedom and not discrimination. Read more about the proposal and tell us what you think: http://d-news.co/tS0kb (Photo: AP).

status_message:
What motivates domestic abusers who kill? For the next story in our Deadly Affection series, out this weekend, reporter Sarah Mervosh interviewed 3 inmates convicted of the crime to get insight into the psychology of lethal abusers.

For instance, John Battaglia still portrays himself as a loving father, even as he sits on Death Row in Livingston, Texas. He was convicted of killing his two young daughters in 2001 at his Deep Ellum loft while his ex-wife listened on the phone. Battaglia has been diagnosed with narcissistic personality disorder, in addition to bipolar. Narcissism is characterized by exploitive behavior, an oversized sense of self-importance, and a lack of empathy. 

Battaglia told reporter Sarah he believes he was set up. He blames the D.A., the judge handling his trial, and The Dallas Morning News for his conviction. Narcissists also tend to view themselves as victims, experts say.

We want your perspective. Share it at our ongoing live discussion here: http://d-news.co/tQ8g6.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Clarence Griffith, nearly 101, is powerful medicine for the anxious, scared and tearful in the critical-care waiting room at Baylor University Medical Center at Dallas' cardiac unit, where he's a volunteer host. He has an intuitive gift for knowing what they need: coffee, prayer, maybe just directions to the bathroom. He figures out who needs to talk, and who may just need the quiet human contact of a hand to hold. Mr. Griffith, born in 1913, drives — yes, still — to the hospital because "I want to help people. That's what I'm for." Read more about Mr. Griffith and be inspired: http://d-news.co/tLm30 (Photo: Lara Solt/DMN).

status_message:
Far from the Persian Gulf or South Pacific, Mike Mullen tends his fleet of offshore hotels servicing oil rigs around the world, right from his Preston Road office in Dallas. Yes, -- oil rig hotels. "Accommodation is now a very, very robust part of the business," Mullen says. "It's not economical to transport workers back and forth by boat or helicopter from rigs 100 or 200 miles offshore. You need a nice living environment to appease the workers. And the majors [the big oil companies] are very, very worker-friendly."

Worker-friendly indeed. Mullen's newest rigs, designed to house 354 workers, include TVs in every room, fast internet connections, fitness centers, saunas, and theaters: http://d-news.co/tIQ49 (Photo: CBI Capital).

status_message:
Try to make time for these 2 important heart-health stories today: 

-- It doesn't take all that much extra sugar to substantially raise the risk of fatal heart problems, the biggest study of its kind has found. For instance, having a cinnamon roll with your morning coffee, a super-size sugary soda at lunch and a scoop of ice cream after dinner would put you in the highest risk category in the study: http://d-news.co/tgNmM.

-- Our science writer, Anna Kuchment, reports on recent studies that have found that fat can communicate with the heart and influence the organs around it. Body fat isn't just an inert, squishy substance relentlessly hanging onto our frames; it's actually alive. These and other recent findings are so bombshell, they're turning our understanding of obesity on its head. Find out what other new information these studies are telling us about body fat: http://d-news.co/tgNj8.

status_message:
WATCH: The "Come Together" discussion taking place in the Arts District at 7 p.m. is full, but you can watch it live right here: http://d-news.co/tgT2v. Mayor Mike Rawlings, Potter's House Bishop T.D. Jakes, Dallas immigration lawyer Liz Cedillo-Pereira, and Paul Quinn College president Michael Sorrell will discuss how to bridge the divide between northern and southern Dallas and expand opportunities across the city. 

For instance, Sorrell told us in January that the city must address a historic imbalance between northern and southern Dallas if it aspires to become one of the nation's great cities. It must offer a strong school system, beautiful parks, fine arts opportunities and "a culture that makes people feel we're all in it together."

Agree? What else needs to happen?

The U.S. High Speed Rail Association has proposed a 17,000-mile national high-speed rail system that would be built in four phases, for completion by 2030. This graphic shows connections color coded by possible completion date. 

But making high-speed rail in the U.S. a reality up to now has been a bumpy ride over politics. Writes environmental reporter Randy Lee Loftis: "Hometown feuds, lawsuits and arguments bog high speed rail down. In Texas, the dream of gliding between Dallas and Houston at 200-plus mph is decades old. But in 2014, Dallas to Houston still is by car or bus — or by air with all its bothers. If the idea of Texas high-speed rail is ever to become reality, planners will have to answer questions about more than money and politics. They also must decide what it would mean for the environment."

status_message:
A court ruling in Washington today will mean Dallas-based AT&T and other internet providers  can begin giving more speed — through more bandwidth — to some sites and apps, and less to others. It's a blow to so-called net neutrality. 

If you're not familiar with the term, our Michael Lindenberger, who's in D.C. reporting on the ruling, explains it like this:
-- Companies like AT&T will now be allowed to narrow the bandwidth for, say, a movie-streaming site like Netflix, while giving more capacity to a Netflix rival. The ability to discriminate gives AT&T, Verizon and other internet providers the opportunity to charge fees to firms who want to be able to offer faster experiences to their customers.
-- Net neutrality advocates (those who argue that internet providers should not be allowed to play favorites) argue that providers will now only open powerful, faster bandwidth capacities to firms that are willing to pay for it. That would push out startups or smaller rivals who can't afford it.

Read more and tell us what you think: http://d-news.co/sAzaU (Photo: New York Times).

Jory Enck of Copperas Cove in Central Texas was arrested in October for not returning a library book he checked out three years ago. He told the Killeen Daily Herald that he wouldn't set foot in a library again: "I think I will probably just purchase a book from Amazon." 

Believe it or not, such cases aren't unheard of. A Texas state law took effect in September that defines the failure to return library books as theft, and rising costs have ordinances calling for fines or even arrest warrants when library property isn't returned. Other states also call for fines or arrest warrants in such cases, including Iowa,  Vermont and Maine. 

Read more (and turn in those overdue library books): http://d-news.co/s4Bxt.

A DART bus and two pedestrians negotiated the slick sleet-covered Jefferson Boulevard viaduct between the Omni hotel and the Dallas Morning News early Friday morning. But DART light rail trains couldn't negotiate anything. The entire system was out of service Friday morning through the weekend in what has been the agency's longest down time since trains first started running in 1996. 

DART says it will begin re-exploring options at keeping ice from coating power-providing cable -- just as soon as it gets its 61-mile light rail system fully operational again:  http://d-news.co/rBCIN (Photo: Irwin Thompson/DMN).

Our editorial board wrote this week, "These days, it's increasingly all about 'me' — and my device. JFK photo: About 45 minutes after the president's assassination on Nov. 22, 1963, Dallas Police Officer J.D. Tippit stopped a man walking along 10th Street and Patton Avenue in Oak Cliff. They talked through a passenger window of the patrol car. Then, as Tippit got out and walked toward the front of the vehicle, the man fired three rounds from a .38-caliber revolver. He shot the officer a fourth time as he lay in the street.

Many officers controlling the crowd at the Texas School Book Depository in downtown heard the report of Tippit's shooting at 1:16 p.m. and began to search for the suspect. Tippit's blood can be seen on the street by the officer's foot. 

Read more about Tippit and his family here: http://d-news.co/qL95a (Photo: Darryl Heikes/Dallas Times Herald)  #jfkdallas #jfk50

status_message:
On the day of President Kennedy's assassination on Nov. 22, 1963, Richard Nixon was leaving downtown Dallas just as President Kennedy was arriving. Nixon had lost to Kennedy in the 1960 presidential election and was working as a corporate lawyer.

Nixon was staying at the old Baker Hotel (as was actress Joan Crawford on an unrelated Big D visit). Kennedy stayed in Suite 850 at the Hotel Texas in Fort Worth.

On Nov. 21, Nixon held an informal press conference in his hotel suite (pictured), taking jabs at the Kennedy administration. Kennedy was arriving in Fort Worth from visits to San Antonio and Houston.

On the morning of the assassination, as Kennedy was preparing to speak in Fort Worth, Nixon climbed into a car at Commerce and Akard in downtown Dallas and started off for Love Field. Leaving the Baker behind, he looked toward the overcast sky and saw red, white and blue banners whipping in the wet wind above Main Street.

Read more about Nixon's visit to Dallas, the two rivals' relationship and their crossed paths in Dallas 50 years ago: http://d-news.co/qBGdV (Photo: Tom Dillard/DMN staff).

status_message:
A regional journalism note: The Dallas Morning News will begin printing the Fort Worth Star-Telegram in the first quarter of 2014. The Star-Telegram plans to sell its print site and eliminate the jobs of about 75 full-time and 200 part-time workers. This is only related to the printing of the physical newspaper and not news reporting. Read more: http://d-news.co/qz7DV.

Gary Wortel, president and publisher of the Star-Telegram, said the new printing agreement is a good long-term move for his news organization and will be "transparent" to readers.

Metro newspapers have been battered by digital distribution of news and advertising and revenue has been shrinking for years, causing them to trim staff and expenses and, in some cases, sell assets to raise money. For example, the DMN production plant in southern Dallas County is for sale. 

Share any thoughts.

status_message:
Today's JFK photo comes from Facebook friend Kimberly Murray Huff of Kaufman County, who found it in a box of old family photos. 

It belonged to a late, elderly family member, but Jennifer isn't sure who in the family actually snapped the shot. You can see from the date stamp that whoever took it didn't get it developed until 1967. 

Jennifer is pretty sure it was taken just as the motorcade left Love Field, but she says she'd really like to know exactly where. "I always thought about how close up and clear it was -- and to nab it at that moment. It had to be taken with just a basic camera." 

Thanks to Jennifer for sharing a piece of her family (and Dallas) history.  #jfkdallas #jfk50

The night she was arrested in 2001, Barbara Atkinson told police she loved her daughter Lauren -- just rescued from a locked closet after years of unimaginable abuse -- "with all my heart and soul." Days later, she hardened, telling a CPS investigator, "I never loved Lauren. I never wanted her. When my other kids hurt, I hurt. When Lauren hurt, I felt nothing."

In Part 6 of our series about the life of Lauren Kavanaugh, now 20, we try to plumb the depths of Barbara Atkinson's depraved mind: http://d-news.co/qbYYc. #laurenkavanaugh

status_message:
After Sabrina and Bill Kavanaugh finally gained full custody of Lauren in 2002, they got a crash course on caring for a severely abused child. Thirteen months earlier, Lauren had been rescued from a closet in Hutchins after years of torture at the hands of her mother and stepfather. 

Dr. Barbara Rila, a Dallas psychologist, said Lauren's psyche was injured in many ways, but perhaps the worst was growing up without love. In Part 5 of 8 in our series on the life of Lauren, now 20, we find out how the effects of abuse and neglect followed her, even after becoming part of a loving family: http://d-news.co/q9rzo. #laurenkavanaugh

status_message:
You might remember little Lauren Kavanaugh, the girl found living in a closet in Hutchins in 2001. But you don't remember her like this. This was 7 years before she was found locked in the dark, alone, sitting in her own waste, skin and bones, physically and sexually abused beyond imagination. The story shocked and sickened the entire country.

Now 20, Lauren is attending community college. "The fact she survived all those childhood years of starvation and solitude, much less that she's now attending community college, is miraculous. "The fact that we're talking about her graduating from high school, that she has reflective thoughts, that she has a relationship with her adopted mother, that she can talk about the things that happened in her past," says Dr. Barbara Rila, a Dallas psychologist who specializes in the treatment of severely abused children, "these things are amazing and remarkable."

Lauren is helping us share her story. Read and watch the first installment of our 8-part series here: http://dallasnews.com/lauren. #laurenkavanaugh

status_message:
Ammonium nitrate fertilizer is not allowed in Afghanistan. The fertilizer's explosive nature has led to similar prohibitions in China, Colombia, Germany, Ireland and the Philippines. But in the U.S., you can purchase it pure by the ton. Then you can store it in a wooden warehouse with no sprinkler system, a few hundred feet from a middle school.

For more than a decade, U.S. efforts to tighten controls over ammonium nitrate fertilizer have repeatedly failed, bogged down by bureaucratic gridlock and industry resistance. Regulations approved years ago remain unenforced and unfinished. Mere talk of safer substitutes has been blocked by those with profits at stake.

Read more of our DMN Investigates' latest reporting on ammonium nitrate fertilizer, prompted by the West, Texas, tragedy in April: http://d-news.co/pAvSb.

status_message:
A boycott and vigil are planned today in Farmers Branch over the 7-year-old immigration ordinance that's been stalled in federal courts. Anger percolates on both sides. 

The one-day city boycott is led by Carlos Quintanilla and Victor Quezada, community activists. Quintanilla said certain city leaders want to push out low-income immigrants, whether they're in the U.S. unlawfully or lawfully. 

"The end game is that they want to build up-scale development," said Quintanilla, who lives in Dallas. "They want the nice country-club crowd and not ugly apartments that immigrants live in." 

On the other side, outside attorneys have defended the city, and their persistence has even brought in $600,000 in financing from outsiders, including real estate heir Trammell S. Crow. More: http://d-news.co/oQGug.

It's two miles from Shyam Rai's apartment to the Cheesecake Factory across from NorthPark, where he works nights as a dishwasher. By bicycle, the trip takes the Bhutanese refugee 30 minutes from the home he shares with his wife and baby daughter in Vickery Meadow.

The International Rescue Committee, an organization that assists refugees, gave Rai his bike. For the past two years, the IRC has worked with nonprofit Spokes for Folks to collect and distribute used bikes, as well as lights and the helmets required under Dallas code.

Rai's bike is helping him build a new life. It offers him freedom -- but it exposes him to risks as well.  Dallas has ranked as one of America's worst biking cities.

Read more about Rai and how the IRC helps refugees navigate Dallas transportation: http://d-news.co/owp9e (Photo: Brandon Wade/DMN).

status_message:
For the 50th anniversary of 1963's March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom in 1963, we turned to Arrvel Wilson, founder of the West Dallas Community School and pastor of the West Dallas Community Church, to share his reflections on how that pivotal moment in civil rights history changed things -- for better and for worse. 

-- "I had questioned my father about why I couldn't go to the State Fair except for that one day in October. His explanation was 'that's how it is.' To see Dr. King pulling our people together to bring about change was inspiring."
-- "I think some people thought [King] was a sellout and his way to tackle racism wasn't the best. MLK understood from a biblical perspective that you should actually love your enemies, confront racism in a way that is nonviolent and leave the results to the Lord." 
-- He also remembered that "one of the things the speech did was to create more hostility toward minorities." 

Read more of our Q&A with Pastor Wilson: http://d-news.co/olMB9 #MarchOnWashington #MLK

status_message: Many books, movies and television shows have tried to capture the magical relationship that can exist between a high school football team and the town it represents — particularly in Texas. But a moment in Euless on Tuesday transcended anything Friday Night Lights could come up with, our editorial board writes. About 1,000 students and residents of Euless, which has one of the largest Tongan populations outside Polynesia, turned out for a vigil mourning the loss of two former Euless Trinity High School players — Polo Manukainiu and Gaius Vaenuku — and another Euless teen, Andrew Uhatafe. The three were killed on a New Mexico highway when their SUV rolled over. The ceremony concluded with a moving rendition of "Lean on Me" by the Euless Trinity football team. Stay strong, Trojans. http://d-news.co/nARbr (Photo: Sarah Hoffman/DMN).

The Whole Woman's Health abortion clinic in Beaumont has become an endangered species. It may not be around much longer.

Whole Woman's Health, which serves mostly poor and black women, is the only abortion clinic in the city. The next closest one is 80 miles away in Houston. Health care experts predict that most of the 42 abortion clinics in Texas, including this one, could close if the nation's most restrictive anti-abortion law takes effect as scheduled in September. status_message: North Texas has lost one of its prized works of architecture, a modernist gem in Fort Worth designed in the 1950s by architect Harwell Hamilton Harris. The new owners of the Ruth Carter Stevenson House, commissioned by Amon G. Carter's daughter, preemptively demolished it before preservationists could mount a campaign to spare it, a move our architecture critic calls "an act of brazen philistinism." status_message:
Texas SB 515 would let brew pubs sell their brands in convenience and liquor stores. There are a lot of other smaller laws sitting on Gov. Perry's desk, too, like:

-- Proof of insurance could be shown electronically with a smart phone.
-- No more phone solicitations posing as a questionnaire. 
--  High schools could no longer be sanctioned for allowing such things as sales of candy bars for fundraisers, which had run afoul of prohibitions against the sale of "low nutritional value foods" on campus.
-- Drinks served in elementary and middle schools must be 100 percent vegetable or fruit juice.
-- Voters could apply over the Internet for a voter registration card or renewal.
-- It's OK to say merry Christmas and happy Hanukkah in school and that symbols don't necessarily connote promotion of a religion.
-- The authorization for judges to conduct marriage ceremonies would be extended into their retirement. 

... and several more: http://d-news.co/lsXgL. Tell us what you think.

status_message:
North Texas severe weather update: A severe thunderstorm warning has been issued for Denton, Wise and Jack counties. Most of North Texas still remains under a tornado watch until 7 p.m.

The squall line to the west of Dallas-Fort Worth has formed, but storms haven't formed in front of it. The biggest tornadic threat is south and east of Dallas. "We'll probably see stronger storms in the line, with wind and hail threat. But overall the tornado potential looks about the same as it did before. An isolated tornado can't be ruled out in the Metroplex," says Steve Fano at the National Weather Service. More info: http://d-news.co/lfSbV.

status_message: The date of 4/20 has been a rallying cry for supporters of legalizing marijuana since it was popularized by California teens in 1971. Family columnist Nancy Churnin explains why she thinks Texas should join the nation in its changing attitudes toward legalization: "I say it's time for Texas, which is in the forefront of so much great medical research, to embrace the studies on marijuana and see where they lead. I say it's time for Texas to let this old grudge against marijuana go the way of Prohibition and let people decide for themselves if they want to smoke it recreationally." http://d-news.co/kauWe (Photo: Seattle Times). So, happy 4/20 ...? Tell us your thoughts.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Will Pry, the editor who handles our digital coverage of the 50th anniversary of JFK's assassination, didn't expect his research to turn up an emotional personal connection to the event. But recently in the course of his work, he came across a letter his grandfather wrote to his own parents on Nov. 25, 1963, days after the assassination. One "sentence alone — about demonstrating respect and affection for the president — spoke volumes to me. It confirmed everything I'd read in the reporters' notes, that the people of Dallas were genuinely welcoming to the president that day." Read more: http://d-news.co/jDZyk.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Our auto writer, Terry Box, was driving a 2013 Ram 1500 Longhorn Edition like this one (but copper-colored) last Wednesday, March 20, about 7 p.m. on the Dallas North Tollway. status_message: Update: More on the firing of the (former) voice of Big Tex -- By the time Bill Bragg started negotiating a new contract with the State Fair, his boss had retired, and he was instead reporting to spokeswoman Sue Gooding. I thought I was the voice of Big Tex and they said I'm not because he's not standing up right now. … When the fair closes, my mouth is supposed to close too." status_message: Republican Rep. Joe Barton is a top spender of campaign money to pay relatives, according to a USA Today analysis of campaign money. status_message: Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee from Texas spoke outside the U.S. Supreme Court today alongside demonstrators in support of Section 5 of The Voting Rights of Act of 1965. Heated oral arguments inside the court expose the justices' ideological chasm. One of the more stunning moments came when Justice Scalia called the landmark civil rights law "the perpetuation of racial entitlement," a comment that shocked some spectators and underscored the gap between minority advocates and those who view the case through a lens of federal infringement on states' rights. More about the Voting Rights Act and what is being argued: http://d-news.co/i6IMH (Photo: New York Times). Tell us your thoughts.

status_message: The unique challenges faced by gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgendered seniors are attracting interest from experts who study the field of aging, especially regarding housing and care facilities. When gay seniors enter a nursing home, they tend to go back into the closet for fear of how they will be treated by their peers or even staff. Attitudes toward homosexuality in Dallas are considered progressive, but not in this particular age group.  "Seniors grew up in an era where you were criminal" if you were LGBT, said Cece Cox, chief executive of the Resource Center: http://d-news.co/hMmxD.

status_message: Big education news: State District Judge John Dietz has ruled that the Texas school finance system is unconstitutional. "There is no free lunch. We either want increased standards [in schools] and are willing to pay the price, or we don't," he said from the bench. "There is a cost to act, namely a tax increase. There is also a cost not to act, the lost of our competitive position as a state." The case is likely headed to the state Supreme Court. More: http://d-news.co/hpR2y (Photo: AP).

status_message:
Update on Kaufman County DA Mark Hasse's shooting death: 

-- Kaufman Police Chief Chris Aulbaugh says Dallas County DA Craig Watkins "made a mistake" earlier when Watkins told the media an arrest had been made.
-- District Attorney Mike McLelland said that his department had worked on Aryan Brotherhood cases in the last two years but that as far he knew, Hasse was not currently working on one, like was reported earlier.
-- Hasse was said to be armed, typically, but it was unknown whether he was carrying a gun today when he was assaulted on the walk to the office after he'd parked his vehicle.
-- Aulbaugh and Kaufman County Sheriff David Byrnes confirmed that the crime had the look of a "hit," that Hasse was specifically targeted.

Press conference video and more: http://d-news.co/hjugr (Photo: David Woo/Staff).

status_message: The new $60 million Allen Eagle stadium was paid for with local bonds and not state funds, but such pricey projects don't help districts in trying to sway public support for restoring funding lost to budget cuts, some educators say. Since the Legislature convened this month for the first time since slashing $5.4 billion in school spending, majority Republicans have shown they're in no hurry and under no intense pressure to put that money back. School allies say blundering districts simply lost the public relations battle to win support. "They've done an absolutely terrible job in making their case to the public," says lobbyist Tom Archer. But education leaders say they've tried. Read more: http://ow.ly/hd0Jk. What are your thoughts on the historic education cuts and the way school districts have -- or haven't -- tried to get public sympathy?

status_message: Another tragic story from the superstorm is the sinking of the famed HMS Bounty. From our editorial writer Tod Robberson: "On the scale of most-terrifying experiences in my life, I put the 36 hours I spent in the Atlantic aboard a sailboat during a major spring storm in 2009 right up there with being kidnapped and shot at in Iraq, Afghanistan and El Salvador. Despite what I know about sailing in sub-hurricane weather, I don't know the half of what conditions were like aboard the HMS Bounty before it sank Monday and, apparently, took its captain with it." Read more: http://dallasne.ws/VC8KYc (Photo: AP).

status_message: It's among the most constant complaints leveled by readers of this newspaper, a variation on the theme: You people don't know where my neighborhood actually is. status_message: Marvin Hamlisch, seen here with Barbra Streisand in November, died this morning. He was the composer behind 'A Chorus Line,' 'The Way We Were,' 'The Sting' and 'Ordinary People' and was a household name in the '70s and '80s. His local ties include being principal pops conductor for the Dallas Symphony Orchestra and working with kids from Booker T. He is also but one of 11 people to have won an Emmy, a Grammy, an Oscar, a Tony AND a Pulitzer. Hamlisch, 68, was busy and had a full schedule ahead of him (Photo: AP). Read more on the latest about his death and view condolence tweets: http://bit.ly/OWzOkI.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message: Taiwanese photographer Tou Chih-kang hangs his portraits of the final moments in the lives of shelter dogs for a public exhibition in Taoyuan, northern Taiwan. Tou has been visiting dog shelters for two years taking human-like portraits that give a sense of dignity and esteem to the canines. His aim is to educate the public on the proper care of pets. This year Taiwanese authorities will kill an estimated 80,000 stray dogs throughout the island. (Photo: AP)

status_message: Dallas woodcarver Walter Wharton, 78, of Dallas, crafts eagle canes for wounded Texas veterans in a small backyard shed. He's a retired lieutenant colonel with 23 years in the army and the son of a cavalry man. He started Operation Cane of Texas, which has chiseled more than 600 canes since it began in 2004. Despite the fact that they are beautifully carved and painted, the Veterans Administration doesn't consider the canes to be regulation issue. Wharton says the canes are fully functional and can be altered to the particular veteran's height. Read the story here: http://dallasne.ws/OCpREJ

status_message: In this 1965 AP file photo, we're given The Twist in action. Today the Federal Reserve announced that it's extending its "Operation Twist" program, which is named after the dance craze in an a nod to economic history when the Kennedy administration cut long-term rates while leavings short-term rates alone in the early 1960s. Read the Business story here: http://dallasne.ws/LBK3Z8. The program is designed to spur borrowing and spending. Will it?

status_message: From staff writer Talia Richman -- The U.S. government has stepped into a dispute involving a fossilized dinosaur sold last month for more than a million dollars by Dallas-based Heritage Auctions, which auctioned off the nearly complete Tyrannosaurus bataar in New York City on May 20 for $1,052,500. The sale proceeded even after a Texas judge issued a restraining order in a suit filed by the Mongolian government claiming ownership of the dinosaur, which hunted herbivores 70 million years ago across what is now Mongolia's Gobi Desert. Read the rest of the story here: http://bit.ly/MmXH3C

status_message: HISTORICAL SERIES: One weekend in June 1892, Isaac Bruce traveled to Hillsboro to celebrate Emancipation Day. But by the end of the festivities, Bruce had lost his freedom after being falsely accused of rape. The Bruce case led to deep soul-searching in a racially charged Lone Star State. It began with the approach of Juneteenth, the anniversary of the day Texas slaves learned they'd been freed. We retraced Bruce's journey from the scene of the crime, to the square where a sheriff and armed residents held off a lynch mob, to the courthouse where his trial occurred and to the jail where he was held while the scaffolding for his hanging was being built. Ponder Bruce's story -- Read the installments and view a timeline, slideshow and old newspaper articles here: http://dallasne.ws/NG2bnT; and take a 360-degree interactive look of the tomblike cell beneath the Ellis County jail cell where he was kept here: http://dallasne.ws/KO8AsP. THIS PHOTO: Chain rings still remain inside the old Ellis County jail death cell where Bruce spent time before being exonerated by Governor Hogg.
link_name: Timeline Photos

Raise Your Voice! We are actively seeking applications for new Voices Columnists.
The deadline to apply to become a Voices volunteer columnist is noon on Monday, April 30. What makes someone a good Voices columnist? They have something to say, and they want to learn from professional editors how to get better at saying it. Volunteer columnists write regular columns for one year, sharing with readers information from their communities and from their lives that is both interesting and persuasive. They focus on local and personal topics where they have unique insight, leaving the political talking points and pontifications to the pundits.
